The optical behavior of L-CDs was further examined by time-resolved PL spectroscopy and the PL decays can be fitted by a two-component exponential (
                        Fig. S4
                      and 
                        Table S1
                     ). The lifetime of the short-lived and long-lived component were about 3.04 ns and 8.26 ns, which were assigned to the recombination pathways of the core states and surface functional groups, respectively. The absolute quantum yield of L-CDs was determined to be 33.55 % by a quantum efficiency measurement system with a calibrated integrating sphere (
                        Table S2
                     ). Additionally, the PL intensity of chiral CDs almost remained stable even if irradiating continuously for 1 h under a 150 W Xe lamp, placing for one week, within the pH range of 4–10 and under the concentration of NaCl reached 0.5 M, indicating their excellent resistance to photobleaching (
                        Fig. S5 and S6
                     ). And the experimental results on stability against photobleaching suggest the absence of additional fluorescent small molecule by-products.

The surface functional groups of L-/D-CDs and chiral precursors L-/D-Trp were further investigated by FTIR spectroscopy (
                        Fig. S9
                     ). For chiral CDs, a broad and intense band at 3200–3600 cm−1 is attributed to the stretching vibration signals of C-OH and C-NH. Peaks observed in the region of 2850–2923 cm−1 are typical for the sp3 CH stretching vibration. The vibrational absorption signals at 1630 cm−1 and 1501 cm−1 should belong to the bending vibrations of CO and CC, respectively [44]. Peaks appeared in the region 1260–1457 cm−1 represent the stretching of CO and a prominent peak at 1108 cm−1 can be attributed to the stretching vibrations of −C = ONH [63], while there is no peak of −C = ONH on L-/D-Trp. These conclusions are in good agreement with the FTIR spectral characteristics of five chiral CDs samples synthesized by Ananya et al. [45], suggesting that L-/D-CDs consisted of O, N-doped carbon networks rich in hydroxy and amide groups, which also match the XPS results.

The validation and structural features of the L-/D-CDs were further investigated using NMR spectroscopy (
                        Fig. S10
                     ). The 1H NMR spectra of both L-CDs and D-CDs display obviously broad signals in the aliphatic (3–5.5 ppm) and less intense wide peaks in aromatic (6–8 ppm) regions respectively, indicating the H atoms experience a different environment and slow rotation in the L-/D-CDs and confirming the observed properties are coherent with the characteristic of nanoparticles [64,65]. And a new signal near 171 ppm reveals the presence of amide groups in the 13C NMR spectra of L-/D-CDs [66]. Although sharp signals are also observed in the 1H/13C NMR simultaneously, which are consistent with the NMR characteristics of majority reported CDs [29,30,36,64,67]. It seems that surface functionalized CDs will have more or less sharp peaks along with broad peaks in the 1H NMR spectrum even after thorough purification. This phenomenon may theoretically be related to the potential abundant and diverse precursor molecular residues in the surface layer of carbon nanoparticles that form a core–shell structure through the carbonization and polymerization process, which may significantly contribute to the sharp peaks in the NMR spectrum of synthesized CDs.

Independent CPL spectroscopy measurements of L-/D-CDs were also implemented to explore their excited state chirality. Unfortunately, no symmetrical and smooth CPL signal is detected in their optimal emission range, which proves that L-/D-CDs themselves are not CPL active (
                        Fig. S12
                     ). Based on the above glum Equation, molecular structures that have large degree of circular polarization generally have low electric dipole strength. The low electric dipole strength implies either low quantum yield for luminescence or long excited state lifetimes, both of which are detrimental for single molecule spectroscopy. For many chiral chromophoric molecules including our L-/D-CDs. They feature a flat system of π-electrons featuring high local symmetry with the stereocenters being present in an aliphatic side chain. The remoteness of stereocenters from the active chromophoric part then often results in a perturbation of the π electrons that is not strong enough to induce sufficient electric and magnetic character in the transition to give rise to measurable circular polarization [74].

At present, the most mainstream strategy to impart CPL activity to CDs is the co-assembly of “host–guest”, in which chiral CDs serve as a potential luminescent counterpart for supramolecular self-assembly with chiral template hosts. However, the available chiral templates are still extremely limited and urgently awaiting expansion. To our surprise, we found that our L-/D-CDs could trigger Fmoc-Glu to self-assemble into chiral hydrogels. The self-assembly process was carried out in aqueous solution and the racemic mixture of Fmoc-Glu (L or D enantiomers) was not used in this study. It is worth noting that Fmoc-Glu itself cannot self-assemble into hydrogels without L-/D-CDs, some gel factors such as chiral amino acid molecules or nucleotide derivatives are usually necessary to trigger the hydrogelation of Fmoc-Glu [75,76,77], which means that L-/D-CDs not only act as doped fluorophores, but also play a crucial role as chiral inducers in the self-assembly of Fmoc-Glu. Moreover, Fmoc-L-Glu/L-CDs and Fmoc-D-Glu/d-CDs were found to form a brownish yellow opaque hydrogel, respectively. On the contrary, construction of hydrogel was failed in Fmoc-L-Glu/D-CDs and Fmoc-D-Glu/L-CDs (
                        Fig. S13
                     ), which may be due to the stereoselective interaction of biological homochirality is conducive to the increase of intracolumnar order and chiral amplification and enhancement, while the thermodynamic favorability of supramolecular polymerization and the long-range helical order of self-assemblies is diminished or destroyed by heterochirality [78,79,80]. Concentration optimization experiments were performed to determine the optimal ratio between L-/D-CDs and Fmoc-Glu capable of forming a hydrogel, (
                        Fig. S14

                     ). Furthermore, as a control experiment, L-/D-Trp were used instead of L-/D-CDs to assemble with Fmoc-Glu under the same experimental conditions (
                        Fig. S15 and S16
                     ). Fmoc-L-Glu/L-Trp and Fmoc-D-Glu/D-Trp were found to form a suspension with obvious precipitation. Their CD spectra showed the Cotton signals were basically coincident with the characteristic peaks of L-/D-Trp and Fmoc-Glu. Besides, the fluorescent dye ThT was also introduced into the co-assembly process to achieve CPL measurements. Similarly, There is no hydrogel was formed and no CPL signal peak was observed within the emission peak range of ThT. These evidences indicated that there is no interaction between L-/D-Trp and Fmoc-Glu.

Then, CPL spectra was used to study the excited-state chiralities of the co-assemblies as shown in Fig. 2
                     d. It was exciting to find that a wide R-CPL signal ranging from 475 to 650 nm with a peak at 550 nm exhibited in the Fmoc-L-Glu/L-CDs hydrogel, whereas a mirror L-CPL signal appeared in the Fmoc-D-Glu/D-CDs hydrogel. The λmax of CPL signal blue-shifted in contrast to fluorescence emission spectra can be attributed to the formation of H-bonds between Fmoc-Glu and chiral CDs during co-assembly.[85] Obviously, the chiral emission properties of two assemblies bear out that the chiral CDs originally serving as luminophores can trigger the co-assembly with Fmoc-Glu by chiral induction effect in one-step to achieve CPL with a maximum |glum| value of 0.012 (
                        Fig. S19
                     ), which was comparable to the majority of other CDs-composited CPL systems ranging from 10-3 to10-2.[33,36,39,86] Additionally, the melting temperature and thermal stability of two hydrogels were investigated (
                        Fig. S20
                     ). The initial dissociation temperature was 25 ℃ in both, as the temperature increased to 60 ℃, they gradually decomposed into a thick brown-yellow molten liquid, whose CPL signal gradually approached zero, indicating that the gel structure was completely destroyed, and their melting temperature was approximately 40 ℃. And during the five cyclic heat treatments, both hydrogels showed excellent CPL recovery and thermal cycle stability.

Since the chiral hydrogels successfully realized the CPL of L-/D-CDs as one of the assembly units, their potential chiral template functions were considered for further development. Four typical commercial dyes (ThT, TO, PY, TMPyP4) were selected for co-doping with two hydrogels to evaluate their wide applicability to achiral fluorophores (Fig. 3
                     a and 
                        Fig. S21
                     ), respectively. The SEM images of ThT-doped hydrogels proved that addition of the dye did not affect the formation of left-/right-handed nanostructures of chiral hydrogels (
                        Fig. S22
                     ). The optical and fluorescent microscope images of dye-doped hydrogels also showed that the dye molecules are effectively embedded and well dispersed without aggregation quenching (
                        Fig. S23
                     ). In addition, in the CD spectra of four achiral dyes-doped hydrogels (
                        Fig. S24
                     ), it can be seen that their symmetric CD responses in the range of 200–250 and 250–310 nm respectively corresponded to the intrinsic signals of chiral molecules and helical packing of Fmoc chromophore, which is similar to that of the original hydrogels. However, new mirror CD signals respectively appeared near 420, 500, 550 and 440 nm, which could be ascribed to chromophores of dye molecules and consistent with their respective absorption band, indicating that chirality of dyes was induced in the matrix of chiral hydrogels. And the CPL spectra of hydrogels containing different dyes were monitored as shown in Fig. 3
                     b and 
                        Fig. S25
                     . Fortunately, symmetrical CPL signals centered at around 490, 560, 610 and 700 nm were respectively observed in spectra of ThT/TO/PY/TMPyP4-doped hydrogels and their |glum| values all reached 1 × 10-2, which were equivalent to the initial hydrogels. Furthermore, as a control experiment, L-/D-Trp were used instead of two chiral hydrogels to interact with four dye molecules (
                        Fig. S26
                     ). Their CD spectra only showed Cotton signals belonging to L-/D-Trp, and no new CD signals appeared at the absorption peaks of each dye. Moreover, the CPL spectra did not show obvious signal peaks, indicating that the dye molecule was not induced to exhibit chirality by L-/D-Trp and there is no interaction between them. These results strongly confirm that the formation of the nanohelical co-assembly structure was necessary to serve as valid matrices to induce chirality of dye molecule,[76] and our chiral hydrogels can indeed be developed as a new chiral template to achieve effective chiral transfer to achiral moiety, and the full-color CPL can be easily achieved by flexibly adjusting the dyes intercalated in template.
